SIMPLE: gossip
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gossip
<hw>Gos"sip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>gossib</ets>, <ets>godsib</ets>, a relation or sponsor in baptism,
a relation by a religious obligation, AS. <ets>godsibb</ets>, fr.
<ets>god + sib</ets> alliance, relation; akin to G. <ets>sippe</ets>,
Goth. <ets>sibja</ets>, and also to Skr. <ets>sabh⟦amac⟧</ets>
assembly.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A sponsor; a godfather or a godmother.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Should a great lady that was invited to be a <qex>gossip</qex>, in
her place send her kitchen maid, 't would be ill taken.</q>
<rj><qau>Selden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A friend or comrade; a companion; a familiar and
customary acquaintance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My noble <qex>gossips</qex>, ye have been too prodigal.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who runs house to house, tattling and telling
news; an idle tattler.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The common chat of <qex>gossips</qex> when they meet.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The tattle of a gossip; groundless rumor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bubbles o'er like a city with <qex>gossip</qex>, scandal, and
spite.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gossip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gossip
<hw>Gos"sip</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To stand sponsor to.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gossip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Gossip
<hw>Gos"sip</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Gossiped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Gossiping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make
merry.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To prate; to chat; to talk much.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To run about and tattle; to tell idle
tales.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gossiper</ent>⟦br⟧
